      <hedline>
        <hl1>Practicing Compassion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elizabeth Clark letter cites importance of compassion in medical care; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Compassion is not learned in the classroom. One must identify with the patient and experience his suffering to assist in his recovery. As a hospital volunteer I have observed that listening and communicating have great curative powers. A patient's need to be heard and to resolve his fears is as inherent to his well-being as medical care.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Compassion is not learned in the classroom. One must identify with the patient and experience his suffering to assist in his recovery. As a hospital volunteer I have observed that listening and communicating have great curative powers. A patient's need to be heard and to resolve his fears is as inherent to his well-being as medical care.</p>
        <p>Compassion can be a smile, a touch or a kind word. It can make the difference in a person's healing.</p>
        <p>ELIZABETH CLARK  Oyster Bay, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
